## 1. Broken Access Control

### Vulnerable sample

```javascript
app.get('/profile/:userId', (req, res) => {
    User.findById(req.params.userId, (err, user) => {
        if (err) return res.status(500).send(err);
        res.json(user);
    });
});
```

### Security flaw

This endpoint trusts the `userId` in the URL and returns that record without checking whether the requester is authenticated or authorized to view it. That is an insecure direct object reference (IDOR), a common Broken Access Control issue. Any user who can guess another user’s ID can read another profile.

### Secure version

See [01_broken_access_control_express.js](</Users/cadeau/SDEV245-Security & Secure Coding/OWASP - Code Fix/01_broken_access_control_express.js>).

### Why the fix improves security

The fix requires authentication, validates the identifier, checks that the requester is either the owner or an admin, and only returns safe fields. That enforces server-side authorization instead of trusting client input.

### Official OWASP references

- [OWASP Top 10 2025: A01 Broken Access Control](https://owasp.org/Top10/2025/A01_2025-Broken_Access_Control/)

## 2. Broken Access Control

### Vulnerable sample

```python
@app.route('/account/<user_id>')
def get_account(user_id):
    user = db.query(User).filter_by(id=user_id).first()
    return jsonify(user.to_dict())
```

### Security flaw

This Flask route has the same core problem: it exposes account data for any supplied `user_id` without confirming the caller’s identity or ownership. An attacker can enumerate user IDs and retrieve other accounts.

### Secure version

See [02_broken_access_control_flask.py](</Users/cadeau/SDEV245-Security & Secure Coding/OWASP - Code Fix/02_broken_access_control_flask.py>).

### Why the fix improves security

The updated route uses `@login_required`, compares the target account to the logged-in user, permits admins explicitly, and returns a safe DTO. This changes access from “whoever asks” to “only authorized users.”

### Official OWASP references

- [OWASP Top 10 2025: A01 Broken Access Control](https://owasp.org/Top10/2025/A01_2025-Broken_Access_Control/)

## 3. Cryptographic Failures

### Vulnerable sample

```java
public String hashPassword(String password) throws NoSuchAlgorithmException {
    MessageDigest md = MessageDigest.getInstance("MD5");
    md.update(password.getBytes());
    byte[] digest = md.digest();
    return DatatypeConverter.printHexBinary(digest);
}
```

### Security flaw

MD5 is broken for password storage because it is fast and obsolete. Fast hashes make offline cracking easier, and the sample also omits a unique salt. That means identical passwords produce identical hashes and are vulnerable to rainbow table attacks.

### Secure version

See [03_cryptographic_failures_java.java](</Users/cadeau/SDEV245-Security & Secure Coding/OWASP - Code Fix/03_cryptographic_failures_java.java>).

### Why the fix improves security

The replacement uses PBKDF2-HMAC-SHA256 with a cryptographically secure random salt and a high work factor. That slows brute-force attacks and ensures the same password does not hash to the same stored value across users.

### Official OWASP references

- [OWASP Top 10 2025: A04 Cryptographic Failures](https://owasp.org/Top10/2025/A04_2025-Cryptographic_Failures/)
- [OWASP Password Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)

## 4. Cryptographic Failures

### Vulnerable sample

```python
import hashlib

def hash_password(password):
    return hashlib.sha1(password.encode()).hexdigest()
```

### Security flaw

SHA-1 is also outdated and too fast for password storage. Like the Java example, it lacks a salt and does not use a password-specific key derivation function.

### Secure version

See [04_cryptographic_failures_python.py](</Users/cadeau/SDEV245-Security & Secure Coding/OWASP - Code Fix/04_cryptographic_failures_python.py>).

### Why the fix improves security

The Python fix uses `hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac()` with a random salt and constant-time verification via `hmac.compare_digest()`. This makes password cracking significantly harder and avoids leaking comparison timing.

### Official OWASP references

- [OWASP Top 10 2025: A04 Cryptographic Failures](https://owasp.org/Top10/2025/A04_2025-Cryptographic_Failures/)
- [OWASP Password Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)

## 5. Injection

### Vulnerable sample

```java
String username = request.getParameter("username");
String query = "SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = '" + username + "'";
Statement stmt = connection.createStatement();
ResultSet rs = stmt.executeQuery(query);
```

### Security flaw

This is classic SQL injection. User input is concatenated directly into a query string, so an attacker can inject SQL syntax such as `' OR '1'='1` to bypass filters or extract data.

### Secure version

See [05_injection_sql_java.java](</Users/cadeau/SDEV245-Security & Secure Coding/OWASP - Code Fix/05_injection_sql_java.java>).

### Why the fix improves security

The fix uses a parameterized query through `PreparedStatement`. The database treats the username as data, not executable SQL, so attacker-controlled input cannot change query structure.

### Official OWASP references

- [OWASP Top 10 2021: A03 Injection](https://owasp.org/Top10/2021/A03_2021-Injection/)

## 6. Injection

### Vulnerable sample

```javascript
app.get('/user', (req, res) => {
    // Directly trusting query parameters can lead to NoSQL injection
    db.collection('users').findOne({ username: req.query.username }, (err, user) => {
        if (err) throw err;
        res.json(user);
    });
});
```

### Security flaw

This route trusts a query parameter without type or format validation. In a Node/Mongo stack, attacker-controlled input can sometimes be coerced into operators or unexpected objects, leading to NoSQL injection or logic bypass.

### Secure version

See [06_injection_nosql_javascript.js](</Users/cadeau/SDEV245-Security & Secure Coding/OWASP - Code Fix/06_injection_nosql_javascript.js>).

### Why the fix improves security

The secure version enforces that `username` is a plain string, validates it against an allowlist pattern, and queries with an explicit equality operator. It also excludes sensitive fields from the response.

### Official OWASP references

- [OWASP Top 10 2021: A03 Injection](https://owasp.org/Top10/2021/A03_2021-Injection/)

## 7. Insecure Design

### Vulnerable sample

```python
@app.route('/reset-password', methods=['POST'])
def reset_password():
    email = request.form['email']
    new_password = request.form['new_password']
    user = User.query.filter_by(email=email).first()
    user.password = new_password
    db.session.commit()
    return 'Password reset'
```

### Security flaw

This is not just a coding mistake; it is a design failure. Anyone who knows an email address can reset that account’s password. The flow has no identity proof, no one-time token, no expiration, no hashing, and no abuse controls.

### Secure version

See [07_insecure_design_password_reset.py](</Users/cadeau/SDEV245-Security & Secure Coding/OWASP - Code Fix/07_insecure_design_password_reset.py>).

### Why the fix improves security

The improved flow requires a reset token, checks expiration, hashes the new password before storage, and invalidates the token after use. That redesign adds proper verification and prevents arbitrary account takeover.

### Official OWASP references

- [OWASP Top 10 2025: A06 Insecure Design](https://owasp.org/Top10/2025/A06_2025-Insecure_Design/)
- [OWASP Password Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)

## 8. Software and Data Integrity Failures

### Vulnerable sample

```html
<script src="https://cdn.example.com/lib.js"></script>
```

### Security flaw

This page loads executable code from a third-party source without verifying integrity. If the CDN or network path is compromised, malicious JavaScript can be delivered and executed in users’ browsers.

### Secure version

See [08_software_data_integrity_failures.html](</Users/cadeau/SDEV245-Security & Secure Coding/OWASP - Code Fix/08_software_data_integrity_failures.html>).

Localhost test link:
[http://localhost:8000/08_software_data_integrity_failures.html#integrity-details](http://localhost:8000/08_software_data_integrity_failures.html#integrity-details)

Run this from the project folder before opening the localhost link:
```bash
python3 -m http.server 8000
```

### Why the fix improves security

The fix adds Subresource Integrity with the `integrity` attribute and uses `crossorigin="anonymous"`. It also adds a Content Security Policy to narrow allowed script sources. Together, those controls help ensure only expected script content runs.

### Official OWASP references

- [OWASP Top 10 2025: A08 Software or Data Integrity Failures](https://owasp.org/Top10/2025/A08_2025-Software_or_Data_Integrity_Failures/)
- [OWASP Subresource Integrity](https://owasp.org/www-community/controls/SubresourceIntegrity)

## 9. Server-Side Request Forgery

### Vulnerable sample

```python
url = input("Enter URL: ")
response = requests.get(url)
print(response.text)
```

### Security flaw

This code fetches any user-supplied URL. An attacker can use it to access internal-only services, metadata endpoints, loopback interfaces, or non-public hosts through the server.

### Secure version

See [09_ssrf_protection.py](</Users/cadeau/SDEV245-Security & Secure Coding/OWASP - Code Fix/09_ssrf_protection.py>).

### Why the fix improves security

The secure version only allows HTTPS, enforces an allowlist of hosts, rejects embedded credentials, resolves DNS, blocks private and special-use IPs, disables redirects, and sets a timeout. Those defenses reduce common SSRF abuse paths.

### Official OWASP references

- [OWASP Top 10 2021: A10 Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF)](https://owasp.org/Top10/2021/A10_2021-Server-Side_Request_Forgery_%28SSRF%29/)
- [OWASP SSRF Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Server_Side_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)

## 10. Identification and Authentication Failures

### Vulnerable sample

```java
if (inputPassword.equals(user.getPassword())) { 
    // Login success
}
```

### Security flaw

This compares the supplied password to a stored password directly, which implies plaintext or reversibly stored credentials. It also uses a normal equality check instead of constant-time comparison. If the database is exposed, all passwords are immediately compromised.

### Secure version

See [10_authentication_failures_java.java](</Users/cadeau/SDEV245-Security & Secure Coding/OWASP - Code Fix/10_authentication_failures_java.java>).

### Why the fix improves security

The secure verifier recomputes a PBKDF2 hash from the submitted password using the stored salt and iteration count, then compares the results with `MessageDigest.isEqual()`. That supports safe password verification without storing plaintext credentials.

### Official OWASP references

- [OWASP Top 10 2021: A07 Identification and Authentication Failures](https://owasp.org/Top10/2021/A07_2021-Identification_and_Authentication_Failures/)
- [OWASP Password Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)

